</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1228,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">
This genus is interpreted here as comprising those 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[749,891,1228,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[749,891,1228,1254]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like species that have just two sense cones on antennal segments III and IV. These species seem to be associated with dead branches, but it remains unclear whether they behave as predators or as fungus-feeders. The 
<typeStatus box="[863,914,1300,1326]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<emphasis box="[1019,1155,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schille" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[1019,1151,1300,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuliginosus">fuliginosus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
has been taken on dead branches, as have 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1939" box="[362,414,1336,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulmi">
<emphasis box="[362,414,1336,1362]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">ulmi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[464,582,1336,1362]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Priesner" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[464,578,1336,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fungicola">fungicola</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kucharczyk" authorityYear="2008" box="[634,752,1336,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zawirskae">
<emphasis box="[634,752,1336,1362]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">zawirskae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from a single female taken in a Malaise trap. Two species described from 
<collectingCountry box="[482,549,1372,1398]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Japan</collectingCountry>
were taken from bamboo, but with no observations as to whether they fed on the green tissues or on fungi associated with dead tissues on these plants, or even on other organisms that also lived on these plants. Three species are here newly transferred to this genus from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[1058,1200,1444,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1058,1200,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Two of these were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K." box="[307,613,1480,1506]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" pagination="2919 - 2978" refId="ref10413" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K. (2007) Australian insects of the Haplothrips lineage (Thysanoptera-Phlaeothripinae). Journal of Natural History, 41, 2919 - 2978. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930701783219" type="journal article" year="2007">Mound and Minaei (2007)</bibRefCitation>
as the only known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[951,1093,1480,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[951,1093,1480,1506]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that have two sense cones on antennal segments III and IV: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Tree" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei, 2007:" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[512,603,1516,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acaciae">
<emphasis box="[512,603,1516,1541]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">acaciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is possibly predatory, having been found breeding within leaves tied together by spiders or Lepidoptera larvae, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Tree" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei, 2007:" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[681,776,1552,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gahniae">
<emphasis box="[681,776,1552,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">gahniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably phytophagous, having been found only in the inflorescences of a species of 
<taxonomicName box="[498,598,1588,1614]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
. The third species here transferred, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Tree" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Mound &amp; Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[1011,1120,1588,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collyerae">
<emphasis box="[1011,1120,1588,1614]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">collyerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is known as a predator on the eggs of mites; it is unusual within this genus because antennal segment IV bears an additional very small sense cone, a condition shared by the new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Tree" authorityYear="2019" box="[643,739,1660,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anarsius">
<emphasis box="[643,739,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">anarsius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described below. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pitkin, B. R." box="[940,1090,1659,1686]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" pagination="221 - 280" refId="ref10649" refString="Pitkin, B. R. (1976) A revision of the Indian species of Haplothrips and related genera (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology, 34, 221 - 280." type="journal article" year="1976">Pitkin (1976)</bibRefCitation>
included 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ananthakrishnan &amp; Jagadish" authorityYear="1971" box="[1203,1278,1660,1686]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilis">
<emphasis box="[1203,1278,1660,1686]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">debilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in this genus, but indicated doubts concerning its relationships. A total of 13 species are here transferred from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1925" box="[1254,1406,1696,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1254,1406,1696,1722]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Xylaplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<emphasis box="[151,336,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1933" box="[151,332,1732,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Mesandrothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesandrothrips</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and a further six species are listed below within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1925" box="[898,1050,1732,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[898,1050,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Xylaplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<emphasis box="[1089,1244,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">incertae sedis</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Okajima, S." box="[1258,1436,1731,1758]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" refId="ref10550" refString="Okajima, S. (2006) The Suborder Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). The Insects of Japan, 2. The Entomological Society of Japan, Touka Shobo Co. Ltd., Fukuoka, 720 pp." type="book" year="2006">Okajima (2006)</bibRefCitation>
provided an extensive diagnosis of this genus. However, most of the listed character states are shared with other 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Minaei &amp; Mound" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[151,305,1804,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplothripini">Haplothripini</taxonomicName>
, and many of the distinguishing character states are prefaced by the caveat “usually” thus rendering the diagnosis operationally ineffective. As a result, the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1925" box="[853,1005,1840,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Xylaplothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[853,1005,1840,1866]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Xylaplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
now comprises 11 species, almost all described from the Palearctic and Australian regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="328" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1228,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">
<emphasis box="[199,322,1912,1937]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="328">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Macropterous 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Minaei &amp; Mound" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[497,648,1912,1938]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplothripini">Haplothripini</taxonomicName>
with 8-segmented antennae; two major sense cones on each of antennal segments III and IV; segment VIII usually slender and constricted to the base; pronotum often with only four pairs of major setae, the anteromarginal setae being scarcely longer than discal setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
